at|
Today we are going to cover 2@c openings. We are going to start with some theory and some thoughts about 2@c openings and then we are going to see examples based in the most accepted modern scheme of responses.|
cp||
at|
So let's start with some basics about 2@c. The fundamental question is: how forcing is 2@c and what do you need to open 2@c?

As usual the answers can change based on partnership agreements but I'm going to base in what's normal:
|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


at|
^-{2@c should be game-forcing so neither player can stop before game.}
^-|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


at|
This eases a lot of bidding problems with very strong hands where the knowledge of an early game force situation will give you more bidding space.

In order to open 2@c you need a strong hand. That doesn't mean you need a lot of points. You can open 2@c with not a lot of points if you have just a few losers. A normal idea is that any 22+ hand or hands with about 3 losers should be opened 2@c.
|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


cs|3|
ht|u|
at|^b{|ih|pSKQJT732H62DATCA2|
at|}|
ht|v|
at|^jTake a look at this hand: not many points, just 14 HCP, but
^jwith such a hand opening 2@c is not out of the question.
^jI'm not saying that you must open 2@c. Opening 1@s can work
^jfine. But if you open 2@c it won't be wrong.|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


nt||
cs|1|
cp|2|
at|^-{ ^*BOpening^*N }
^-|
cs|2|
cp||
at|
Balanced hands with 22+HCP, and strong one suited hands are typical 2@c openings.
|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


at|
With two suited hands many players refrain from opening 2@c because you already lost some bidding space opening 2@C and you are going to lose more space showing your suits. Sometimes the bidding goes too high and neither player can know what to do. So with a two-suited hand unless the hand is very very strong you should try not to open 2@c.

Or if you want an advice:
|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|
^-{Be a happy 2@c opener with one suited hands and 
a solid 2@c opener with 2 suited hands.}
^-|
