at|
Now let's talk about the responses.

Currently there are two schools of responses to a 2@c opening:

The first school is to use 2@d as a negative with the other bids showing positive responses. This was widely used a couple of years ago but now it's losing a lot of ground.
|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|
The modern way is to use 2@d as a "waiting" bid and 2@h to immediately show a double-negative (less than 5HCP), with the other bids showing positive hands and good suits. 

So 2@d is becoming a "catch all" bid. The best definition is:
|
at|
^-{2@d denies a double negative or a positive hand with a good suit.}
^-|
at|
That is the scheme we are going to use today.

If you knew it you can practice it and ask questions. If you didn't know it then it's a good chance to learn it :-).

In my opinion this is the best scheme to learn because most good players are using this and you want to play with good players sooner or later.|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


