nt|Q: After 2NT by opener will responder be forced to bid?
A: First of all 2@c is game-forcing. Once you open 2@c you can't stop below game. That's a fact. The only bid that can be passed is 2NT: 2@c--2x--2NT is 23-24 so with 0 you can pass. Any other rebid but 2NT by the 2@c opener is 100% game-forcing.|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


nt|Q: Is it more logical with weak hand and @s Jxx support to bid only 3@s? Opener knows that partner is very weak.
A: The logic of 3@s and 4@s is the following one: If you have a "good" double negative, your side has more chances of slam. Then you want to preserve bidding space. So you can exchange controls and let the 2@c opener ask what he needs to know.|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


nt|That is why with a better hand you bid 3@s while you bid 4@s with a bad hand. The principle is based on what is called "fast arrival" when your side has established a game forcing situation: ^*IThe less you bid the more you have and the more you bid the weaker you are in context.^*N|
at|
Since 2@c establishes a game forcing situation, this is used here.|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


nt|Q: What about 2@C - 2@H - 3@C - any - 4@C as stopping with 0 points dummy no @C support?
A: 2@c-2@h-3@c is game forcing. 4@c can't be passed in that context.
Q: What does responder bid with good harts, 2NT?
A: Yes, 2NT would be a positive hand with good @h. A good @h suit, KJTxx for example is enough (something else on the side of course).|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


nt|Q: If dummy has zero points does he/she pass next bid?
A: No. I sense you are wondering why is this. Let me give you a short unconvincing explanation.|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


nt|It is true that when you open 2@c you can go overboard. Partner might have 0 and you may not be able to make any game. But you need to sacrifice the possibilty of stopping low in order to have bidding space to determine your best strain when your side does have a game. You may have a slam, a game in NT or in a major or a minor, or a grand slam, lot of possibilities when one hand is very strong.|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


nt|In order to have room to explore all this we sacrifice the chances of stopping below game. It's a good trade.

Q: How often will then 2@H bid put declarer in the wrong hand?
A: Only when opener has a strong hand with hearts.|
